oard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tim1965>Tim1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 146<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/24/03 4:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=396.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Religion versus modernity</span><hr size=1> 1. All fundamentalist, intolerant, theocratic,  and puritanical religions need to become totally extinct.<br>
2. All fundamentalist, and medeival interpetations, <br>
and applications of  all religions need to become extinct.<br>
3. Those religions, and religous interpetations , which are tolerant, openminded, progressive,non-fundamentalist, non-medieval, non-puritanical, non-theocratic   and modernist ,<br>
 do have a place in the in the future, of humanity, and <br>
in the future of the whole universe however for all of time.<br>
Tim <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Administrator</span><br>  Posts: 1011<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/24/03 9:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=396.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Religion versus modernity</span><hr size=1> I agree with point #3 whole heartedly.  Even though I'm a heathen atheist I don't think there's really any threat to society by people who aren't fanatical about forcing us to adhere to their religious beliefs.  I'd throw into the mix of points one and two fanatical atheists who get up in arms everytime city hall puts a nativity scene in the window or whatever.  Some of these atheist fanatics need to chill out before they themselves turn into some inquisition.      <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 2/24/03 9:54:07 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=markix@nuclearspace>MarkIX</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Hotel Magnate</span><br>  Posts: 75<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/24/03 9:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=396.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Religion versus modernity</span><hr size=1> Fanatics of any kind are dangerous because they are divorced from reality (sound like anyone we know <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) it doesn't matter what they are fanatical about.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>spacefaring rodent</span><br>  Posts: 1023<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/25/03 9:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=396.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Religion versus modernity</span><hr size=1> I've been divorced from reality for a long time. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   I totally agree though that people who fanatically follow any ideology can become dangerous and cruel.  There are extreme Libertarians for instance who have gone on sprees shooting police officers, environmentalists who torch everything in sight, communists who are trigger happy for revolution, etc.  <br>
I guess that's what I was trying to get at by picking on fanatical atheists.  I'm wary of anyone who wants to impose their morality on me through the use of government sanctioned force regardless of what type of morality it is.  Of all the political parties out there I feel the libertarians are the least &quot;moral&quot; and therefore not as coercive as the other political entities want to be.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=markix@nuclearspace>MarkIX</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Hotel Magnate</span><br>  Posts: 82<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/26/03 2:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=396.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Religion versus modernity</span><hr size=1> Its the fault of those philosophers that postulated a unversal moral code, while I agree that certain moral directives should be unversal that group is only a subset of any social Moral code in existance today and there is a lot of arguement about the differences. Ithionk that a society can be different from mine and still be moral.<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :evil --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/devil.gif ALT=":evil"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  But if they disagree with me they must be conquered <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :evil --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/devil.gif ALT=":evil"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
(The last bit was a joke folks don't get all stroppy )<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=spacedrive@nuclearspace>Spacedrive</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 59<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/26/03 5:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=396.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Religions</span><hr size=1> The religions you site may or may not have a place in the future of humanity, depending on how they are dealt with. We now see a general coflict between Western/Judeo-Christian philosophy and Islamic philosophy. There are troubling signs that the Islamic philosophy can win by immigration into countries that don't oppose it. France is literally opening the door to internal takeover by this method. An anti-western mindset usually condemns technical or societal advancement. There are many places around the world that are living in the same conditions that existed thousands of years ago.<br>
 Society can stagnate and go backwards, this has occured several times in the past. There are no guarantees that our future will advance or improve. I could imagine we get a large space colony built and it sits in a high Earth orbit and then the second dark age arrives. We don't have the ability to even go to the space colony and we forget how we even built it. 500 years from now our descendents will look at that shining point in the sky and ask in amazement - &quot;how could we have built such things?&quot;.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=markix@nuclearspace>MarkIX</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Hotel Magnate</span><br>  Posts: 85<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/26/03 9:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=396.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Religions</span><hr size=1> Philosophy is a system of thought and Religion is a system of belief (or non-thought if you listen to some people) so they are almost opposite. I woulfd think that the people living in the space colony would have to keep their technology in order to survive, technology is somewhat self sustaining also as the more technology advances the Lower forms of technology spreads so the harder it is to erase and the easier to ascend up the ladder again because you fall a little less each time some say that knowing something is possible is half the way to achieving it, and if humans aren't radically altered then there are always some who will try, of course there are always those who will try to stop them but ignoring the facts doesn't make them go away. Thats why we have technology today.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>spacefaring rodent</span><br>  Posts: 1039<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/27/03 1:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=396.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Religions</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> But if they disagree with me they must be conquered  <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Thems fightin' words.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :smash --><img src=http://pages.prodigy.net/rogerlori1/emoticons/smashf.gif ALT=":smash"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    I think a distinction can be made though between fundamentalism where the tenents of a faith are to be believed at face value and more liberal interpretations where one soaks in the basic ideas of a religion but doesn't believe in the stories literally.  Mythology after all is usually a form of transmitting values and other philosophical ideas that can stand alone in a secular sense.  Hinduism, Buddhism, and Christianity do have philosophical underpinnings since they transmit ideas on what constitutes a proper society and the proper relation of individuals to themselves, others, and nature.  I would say Siddartha Guadama (sp?), for instance,  did a lot of reasoning when he put forth the pillars of Buddhism, i.e. attachment as the root of misery, etc.  Joseph Campbell has written a number of good books that touch on the philosophical roots of religions.  Anyhow, we will never stamp out spirituality completely, it'll just take on new forms.  Our brains our hardwired to commune with some &quot;higher power&quot; whether it be nature, anthropomorphic gods, or whatever. <br>
